Here's the implementation of the maxSubarraySum function in C++:

```cpp
#include <iostream>
#include <vector>

int maxSubarraySum(const std::vector<int>& arr, int start, int end) {
    // Base case: array with only one element
    if (start == end) {
        return arr[start];
    }

    // Calculate the midpoint
    int mid = (start + end) / 2;

    // Recursively calculate the maximum subarray sum in the left and right halves
    int leftMaxSum = maxSubarraySum(arr, start, mid);
    int rightMaxSum = maxSubarraySum(arr, mid + 1, end);

    // Calculate the maximum subarray sum that crosses the midpoint
    int leftSum = INT_MIN;
    int rightSum = INT_MIN;
    int sum = 0;

    // Calculate the maximum sum of any subarray that ends at the midpoint
    for (int i = mid; i >= start; i--) {
        sum += arr[i];
        leftSum = std::max(leftSum, sum);
    }

    sum = 0;

    // Calculate the maximum sum of any subarray that starts from the midpoint
    for (int i = mid + 1; i <= end; i++) {
        sum += arr[i];
        rightSum = std::max(rightSum, sum);
    }

    // Calculate the maximum subarray sum that crosses the midpoint
    int crossMaxSum = leftSum + rightSum;

    // Return the maximum value among leftMaxSum, rightMaxSum, and crossMaxSum
    return std::max(std::max(leftMaxSum, rightMaxSum), crossMaxSum);
}

int maxSubarraySum(const std::vector<int>& arr) {
    // Call the helper function with the start and end indices of the array
    return maxSubarraySum(arr, 0, arr.size() - 1);
}

int main() {
    std::vector<int> arr = {-2, 1, -3, 4, -1, 2, 1, -5, 4};
    int maxSum = maxSubarraySum(arr);
    std::cout << "Maximum subarray sum: " << maxSum << std::endl;
    return 0;
}
```

In this implementation, the maxSubarraySum function takes an array `arr` and the start and end indices of the array. It uses a helper function to recursively calculate the maximum subarray sum.

The helper function handles the base case where the array has only one element. Then, it calculates the midpoint of the array and recursively calls itself on the left and right halves. It also calculates the maximum subarray sum that crosses the midpoint.

The maximum subarray sum that crosses the midpoint is calculated by iterating through the left half of the array in reverse order and updating the value of `leftSum` by adding each element. Similarly, it iterates through the right half of the array and updates the value of `rightSum`. Finally, it calculates the maximum subarray sum that crosses the midpoint by adding `leftSum` and `rightSum`.

The main function creates an array, calls the `maxSubarraySum` function, and prints the maximum subarray sum. In this case, the expected output is `6`, which is the maximum subarray sum of the given array.

